{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_eustachy_ver01/data/sn83030214/00206532543/1920080301/0095.xml":{"full_text":"'Stocks Tumble,\n?Many Reaching\nNew Low Level\nuncertainties in Financial\nOutlook and Rumor of\nRasso Polish Armistice\nTerms Take Market Down\n?Crash Folio w s Gains\nRate Decision Outweighed\nin Sensational Decline;\nIndustrials Hit Hard\nt'.'.ccrtaintirs in the financial and\nbusiness outlook, coupled with the ru?\nmors of the publication of Soviel\nRussia's armstice terms to Poland, out\n?eighed the effect of the favorable rat?\nn of the Interstate Commerce\nCommission on the Stock Exchange yes\nterday? and after n rise in price durinj\nthe r.rst half hour's trading, stock.'\ntumbled for the rest of the day unti\nf. .vc clo<e the industrial average ha<\nfound a new low level for the year\nUnited States Steel common, afte\ni opening up a point at 89, droppei\nto 85^j the lowest price since 1917.\nF.ai.rfcad stocks on their initial trans\naction? showed average gains of fror\n1 to 4 p( ints in the more active issues\nbut before the close of the stock marke\n?essior. much of the earlier rise wa\nwiped out, with some stocks showin,\na decline from Saturday's last sales\nNew York Central, Baltimore Ohi(\nRock Island preferred stocks. Lehig\nValley. Norfolk Western and South\nern Railway retained enough of thei\negrlier advances to still show net gain\n?t the close.\nStocks at Lowest Levels\nLiquidation in the industrials wa\nheaviest in the last hour, when pre\nfessionai traders, leading the attacl\nwere successful in bringing about th\nlowest pr.cos of the day. Stocks whic\nir.ade new lows for the year, in add\ntion to Steel common, included Amer\ncan Can, American Smelting p.nd Refir\ning. American Woolen. Bethlehem Stee\nCentra! Leather, Chandler Motors, Mic\nvale Steel, United States Rubber an\nUnited States Industrial Alcohol.\nSome of the net losses for the da\nwere United States Steel, 2ti Unit?\nStates Rubber, 3-%; Studebaker, 2 M\nVanadium Steel, C-H; Stromberg Ca\nburetor, f1 Reading, 2Vfe; Mcx?c?\nPetroleum, SV?; Crucible Steel, 4M\nCorn Products, 2^?; Chandler Motor\n64; Bethlehem Steel, 57s; Ba.dw\nLocomotive, 47*; Atlantic, Gulf We\nIndies, 5ai; American Woolen, 4-\\,ar\nAmerican Can, 3U.\nDespite the heavy losses suffered\nthe stock market, railroad executiv?.\nbankers and industrial leaders co\ntinned to make favorable comment\nthe Interstate Commerce Commissioi\ndecision, which will increase railro\nrevenues by approximately $1,50\n000,000.\nCharles Hayden, chairman of t\nChicago, Rock Island Pacific, said\nbelieved the rate increases grant\nwere perfectly satisfactory. \"Ho\never,\" he added, \"it is nothing mc\nthan the Interstate Commerce Co\nmission should have done and I\npleased that it took the action it d\nThere is one point in the situatii\nhowever, and that is that the higl\ntariffs should not be considered a n\njon for further wa<ge increases,\nthese increased rates will not cat\nany material increase in eommod\ncosts.\"\nCharles E. Mitchell, president of t\nNational City Company, said tl\nwhile he w?s particularly gratified\nthe prompt action of the Interst;\nCommerce CaunmUsion, he did not ic\n!\"or any flood of new railroad tinanc:\nin the r.iVir future.\nRate Decision Commended\n\"The first grade roads,\" said\nMitchell, \"have already demonstra\ntheir anility to ?obtain funds, but\nsecond grade roads will undoubte\nmeet with difficulties. Much will\npond or. how the ?Increase in rates\naffect individual properties. Only e\nmates can now bo obtained and be\ncannot be floated dn estimates. Hi\never, I am well pleased with the\ncisi?n a.td believe a definite step i\nward has been tai:?* in the rehabil\ntion of railroad credit.\"\nThomas W. Lainont, of J. P. Mor}\nCo.. commended the action of\nInterstate Commerce Commission,\nexpressed the opinion that raih\"'\ncredit cannot be restored to its%\nwar position uri.il the carriers a!\nsufficient earning power to make i\nstock financing practicable..\nW. H. Woodin. president of\nAmerican Car nnd Foundry Compa\n?id: \"This action of the Interst\nCommerce Commiwvion is one of\ngreatest cor.structhve event? that h\nhappened in this country for a long\ntime. This means the placing of cred?\nits of the railroads in such a position\nthat they arc not only enabled to pur?\nchase their ^cry much needed require?\nment!, but. will undoubtedly broaden\nthe market for the issuance o? all\nkinds of railroad securities to provide\nmoney for development.\n\"i '.nink it will be found that a fur?\nther increase in freight rates will be?\ncome necessary. Even with this de?\ncision of the Interstate Commerce Confc\nir.ission it will take some time for the\nroads to placo iheinselvcsflin a po.u';on\nwhere they can adequately hanelle traf?\nfic, and it scorns to nie that with the\nmovement of crops this fall the con?\ngestion will be increased.\"\n\"The award is constructive,\" said F.\nF. Fitzpatrick. president of the Rail?\nway Steel Spring Company. \"The new\nrates should allow th? railroads to\nci.rry out their plans for the purchases\nof additional equipment, make pos?\nsible the movement of a large amount\nof business and have a healthy effect\non the general situation, especially the\ncengestion at the steel milis.\"\nRail Rates\nTo Force Up\nFood Prices\n(Continued from pa? en?)\nas a result of the new rail tariffs as\ndisproportionate,\" said Mr. Jones.\nAusten P. Fox, president of Austen\nP. Fox Co., one of the larg?\nest .commission merchant firms in the\ncity, said:\n\"It is absolutely certain that food\nprices will be increased corresponding\njy with the railway rate increases.\nThere is every indication that food\nprices will go up considerably above\nthe proportion of rate increases. If\nfreight rates in the East are to be\ni increased 40 per cent it is reasonable\n1 to suppose that the increase will be\ni fully reflected in the prices of food\nstuffs. In fact, it may go above that\nfigure, so that food products will be\nI advanced from 6 to S per cept.\"\nMr. Fox's opinion was substantiated\nat the office of the European Trading\nCorporation, another large concern\ndealing in foodstuffs.\nJohn Roper, or John Roper Co.,\ncommission merchants, with offices at\n128 Pearl Street, said:\n\"It is only logical to expect that the\nI increased freight rates will be reflected\ni in higher food prices. I am not in a\nposition to offer any definite opinion,\nj for it remains to be seen what propor\nj tion of the new rates will be borne by\nthe producer and what share will be\npassed on to the consumer.\"\nAt the office of C. F. Rutger3 Co.,\n92 William Street, the opinion was\nconfirmed that higher food prices are\nto be expected.\nj \"We haven't yet had an opportunity\nto study the matter, but it is to be ex\npected that the new freight rates will,\nfor the most part, be added on to the\ncost of foodstuffs,\" said an official of\nthe company. \"The figure may even\ngo above the proportion of the new\nrates. No definite opinion, however, is\npossible until we see how the new rates\nwork out in practice.\"\nAn executive official of the Spartan\nProducts Company, Inc., 120 Broadway,\nj was of the opinion that the increase in\nI food prices will be negligible. He said:\n\"We do not foresee any material in\ncrease in food prices as a result of the\nj new railway rates. Judging by pres\nent market conditions, prices will re\nmain firm for the most part. There\nhas been a distinct downward tendency\ni for some time, and the reported in\n1 creased crops are likely to stimulate\nj this tendency. If the new railway\nrates do have any effect on food prices\ni the increase will be slight. The whole\nj matter cannot be determined until we\nsee how the new rates work out in\npractice.\"\nMerchants Declare Rate\ni Award Emergency Move;\nTo Be Modified Later\nThe railway rate increases on freight\nI and passenger traffic granted by the\nI Interstate Commerce Commission are\nbut a temporary expedient, and modifi\ncations in the new tariffs will prob\nj ably be requested of the Interstate\nj C-immerce Commission as soon as ex\nj pc-rience warrants, according to a\nstatement made public yesterday at the\nj office of the New York Merchants' As\nI sociation. The statement was issued\ni by J. C. Lincoln, traffic manager of the\nassociation.\n\"I look upon the decision purely as an\nemergency act,\" said Mr. Lincoln. \"Tho\nj Interstate Commerce Commission was\nI obliged to issue an order for a blanket\n?dt.?ce in rates because the- railroads\ncould not have waited much longer for\nthe- much needed added revenue.\"\nBoth the railroads and the country,\nhowever, Mr. Lincoln added, were\nwaiting for the increased transporta?\ntion facilities essential to the revival\nof the country's post war industry,\nThomas DeWitt Cuyler, chairman of\ntho Railway Executives' Association, 81\nDELICIOUS AND REFRESHING\n?the hit that saves the day.\nDemand the genuinebyfull name?\nnicknames encourage substitution\nThe Coca-Col a, Co.\natlanta ga.\n\nRoads Said to Have\nChance to Cut Rates I\n\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 2.?\nCompletion of \"the cycle of gov?\nernment management of the rail?\nroad industry\" through increases\nin freight and passenger rates\nwas said to-night by Fairfax Har?\nrison, president of the Southern\nRailway system,/ to leave to the\ncarriers of the country the oppor?\ntunity for \"a constant and pro?\ngressive reduction of rates accom?\npanied by an enlargement of serv?\nice.\"\nBroadway, representing the heads of\nmore than 100 of the leading railroads\nof the nation, yesterday expressed\ngratification at the increases. He said\nthe action of the commission trill go a\nlong way in increasing the efficiency\nand facilities of the nation's lines of\ncommunications.\nIt was estimated on the basis of the\n20 per cent rate increase on passenger\ntraffic granted by the commission that\n50,000 commuters between New York\nand points in New Jersey, within a\nradius of thirty miles from Manhattan,\nwould feel the new rates keenly. In\naddition these commuters will be\nobliged to pay a war tax of 2 per cent\non their base rate.\nAccording to Alfred M. Barrett, Pub?\nlic Service Commissioner, however, pas?\nsenger rater? on the Long Island Rail\n1 road cannot be advanced to more than\nthree cents a mile. Commissioner Bar?\nrett said yesterday that three cents a\nmile is the statutory limitation put\nupon Long Island Railroad passenget\nrates.\nAn application for rate increases\nfrom the Long Island Railroad has been\npending for some time before the Pub?\nlic Service Commission. The applica?\ntion asks for an addition to the three\ncent rate on passenger traffic on the\nSouth Shore, a figure now in effect on\nthe North Shore and main line divi?\nsion, and an increase of 10 per cent on j\ncommutation and family tickets. I\nThe application has been suspended\nuntil September 29, Commissioner Bar- j\nrett said, and may be postponed still\nfurther. It is understood, Tiowever,\nthat the Long Island will get a sub?\nstantial increase in rates, although\nnothing like the 20 per cent passenger\nrate increase granted to railroads en?\ngaged in interstate commerce by the\nInterstate Commerce Commission.\nBusiness Men Say\nNew Rates Will Mean\nA Drop in Prices\nBusiness men who depend on trans\nportation to receive or to ship the\nI commodities in which they deal yes\ni terday appeared to he satisfied with\nthe new rate decision. The general\nopinion seemed to be that, while the\nincreased rates might have a tendency\nto raise prices slightly, this will be\novercome by the more efficient and\nspeedier handling of freight.\nIn some cases a lowering of prices\nis expected to result through the\nspeeding up of freight shipments,\nj which will enable many commodities\nnow being shipped by express, because\nof the abnormal delays in freight\nroutes, to be turned back to their\nI original and proper channels. This\nview was frequently expressed in the\nwholesale dry goods trade, where the\nj normal freight shipments have been\ni superseded during the last few years\nby the more costly but speedier ex?\npress shipments.\nIn general, most of the outgoing\nshipments originating in this city are\nhandled by express. This is particu?\nlarly true of the apparel trades.\nTraffic managers for garment manu?\nfacturing concerns are expecting an\nincrease in freight rates of approxi?\nmately .';0 per cent, but assert that\nthis should have relatively small in?\nfluence on prices, since the transpor?\ntation charge on each garment is\ni small and the increase in most\nI cases will amount to but a few cents,\nj which the retailer, who normally pays\nthe shipping charges, will absorb.\nManufacturers and wholesalers of\nsuch commodities all expressed the\nview that any increase in freight and I\nexpress rat^s will not be passed on to\nthe consumer. The general downward\ntendency of prices, at present, they\nfay, is so pronounced that, competition\nwill force the retailers to absorb the\nincreased cosi, instead of adding it to\ntheir selling prices.\nTraveling salesmen are the hardest\nhit of all classes affected by the in-\ncreased rates. Most of the salesmen\nwork on a flat percentage commission!\nand pay their own traveling expenses.!\nThese, commissions have not been in- j\ncreased with the advance in prices,\nsince higher prices have meant larger'\nselling totals, and, consequently, a\nlarger return for the salesman. An?\nother advance in traveling expense,\nhowever, will cut the salesman's net\nearnings considerably.\nThe national organization of travel?\ning salesmen made an unsuccessful ef?\nfort to have the road salesmen exempt?\ned from the new rate. It is expected\nthat some effort will be made to have\nthe percentage of commissions made\nhigher to offset the salesman's in?\ncreased expense. If this occurs manu?\nfacturers and wholesalers are expected\nto figure the increase as Bales expense,\nand so add it to the price of their com?\nmodities. No move has been made to\ndo this yet, so far as could be learned\nyesterday.\nTextile Mills To Be Affected\nIncreased cost of ?oal, it is expected,\nwill affect the textile factories in New\nEngland and so advance manufacturing*\ncosts. At the same time it is certain\nthat raw materials, such as wool and\nsilk, and to some extent, cotton, will\nremain on the lower levels to which i\nthey have dropped in recent months,\nand somewhat offset the advance In\ncoal.\nBusiness men have complained loud?\nly during the last six months of the\ntremendous amount of money tied up in\ngoods in transportation. With com?\nmercial money ranging around 8 per\ncent, the cost of financing theae goods\nhas been a heavy burden. If the new\nrates will speed up deliveries and re?\nlease some of this \"frozen\" credit and\nmake less bank borrowing at exorbi?\ntant rates possible, the business men\ncontend, they are more than welcome.\nB. O. to Spend Twenty\nMillions for Equipment\n\\Vice-President Says Decision\nWas Made Anticipating a Fa?\nvorable Verdict on Rat? lune\nSpecial Dispatch to The Tribune\nBALTIMORE, Aug. 2.?The Balti?\nmore Ohio Railroad Company, antici?\npating a favorable decision in the rate\nmatter by the commission, decided to\nexpend $20,000,000 for new equipment,\naccording to George M. Shriver, senior\nvice-president.\nThe company has arranged to expend\nmore than $10,000,000 for the over?\nhauling of every car that is worth re?\npairing. Its own shops are carrying\nout this program, and repairing of 2,700\ncars has been contracted for with\noutside agencies, the cost of this re?\npair work totaling approximately $12,\n500,000.\nThe new equipment locomotives\nand freight cars?costing about $10,\n000,000, according to Mr. Shriver, is to\nbe purchased through a loan negotiated\nI with the National Railways Service\nCorporation, recently formed by S.\nDavies Warfield, president of the Na\ntional Association of Owners of Rail?\nroad Securities.\nThe granting of approximately 40\nper cent increase in freight rates for\nthe Eastern roads, said Mr. Shriver,\nwill not alter the equipment program\nof the Baltimore Ohio, as previously\ndecided upon. With the new equip?\nment the Baltimore Ohio will not\nlack cars to move traffic.\nBaltimore Ohio officials ventured\n'the assertion that the increased wages\ngranted the railroad men should result\n.in much greater efficiency, and that\ni this should enable railroads to giva\nI greatly increased transportation facili?\nties.\nTwenty Shoe Plants Closed\nHAVERHILL, Mass., Aug. 2.?Reject?\ning new wage price lists offered by the\nShoe Workers' Union, twenty cut-sole,\ntop-lift and tap manufacturers failed\nto open their shops to-day. Six hun?\ndred employees are affected. The new\nprice lists are said to call for wage\nincreases ranging from $14 to $18\nweekly. The factories have been em?\nploying only a third of their normal\nforce during the last month.\nTo Close Out at Once\nMEN'S HIGH SHOES\nReduced to\n\n$6.75\nThe remainder of a large ?stock of reliable black\nand tan lace shoes, reduced to a price that will\ninsure immediate selling. Broken lots.\nThese Also Must Go\nMEN'S BLACK HIGH\nSHOES\nReduced to\n$9.50\nThe quality of these shoes will appeal on sight.\nMade on a smart English last, wing vamp. A\nsplendid value and a good range of sizes.\nFourth Floor\nLord Taylor\n38th Street -?FIFTH AVENUE? 39th Street\nQ NE-HALF\nMILLION\nCourthouse Bids\nHeld for Scrutiny\nOf Working Plans\nEstimate Board Will Not\nAward Contract Until\nPrograms Are Received;\nHylan and Curran Clash\nThe Board of Estimate held a spe?\ncial meeting yesterday to hear the\nreport of Comptroller Craig on the\ncompiling of the bids received for the\nerection of the superstructure of the\nnew county court house. The contract\nwas not awarded, aa the board desirei\nte receive the working program of th?\nlewesst bidders, and resolutions wen\npasted requesting them to submit thei\nprograma within ten days.\nBorough President Curran again op\nposed the building of the new cour\nhouse on the ground that the cit;\nmight better put the money.into th\nerection of homes. Mayor Hylan ac\neased the Borough President of play\nI ing \"petty politics,\" and said that th\nmembers of the board should be hone:\nwith themselves.\n\"We all know Curran is a goo\nfellow,\" said the Mayor, \"but he doc\nplay awful cheap politics.\"\n\"Thanks,\" replied Major Currai\n\"but there is no politics in opposin\nan expensive court house at the pre\nent time. The proposed court houi\nwill cost nearer $20,000,000 than tl\nComptroller's figures. That money pi\ninto the building of homes would tal\ncare of between four and five tho\n?and families, which would be bett\nthan building a court house for tl\nconvenience of a few judges.\"\n\"Yea, ye?, we know,\" said the Maye\n\"If you nadn't told the same story\nmany times and ddne other things.\"\nThe Borough President interrupt\nthe Mayor to ask what he meant\n\"other things,\" but the Mayor refus\nto submit a bill of particulars. Jose\nA. Guider, Commissioner of Public I\nWorks of Brooklyn, who was sitting in\nthe board in the absence of Borough\nPresident Riegelmann, said that the\nManhattan Borough President was\npeeved by the monumental blunder of\nhis own party, \"while this administra-\ntion is going to build the courthouse,!\ndo it much cheaper, and return a lot I\nof land to the city.\"\nThe first bids for the construction\nwor| were rejected as being too high,\nespecially the bids on granite super-\nstructure, and on the second Invita-\ntion bids were requested both on gran\nite and limestone, with the result that\nthe second bids on granite were $701.\n000 less than the first bids. The bids\nfor limestone were $127,000 less than\nfor granite, and Guy LoweU, nrchitcct\nof the building, recommended that the\ndifference was so small that the .~uper-\nstructure be erected of granite.\nComptrc^cr Craig said that the\nstructure could be erected in twelve\nmonths, with the exception of the por?\ntico and the granite pillars at the en?\ntrance. He said that he hoped the\njustices' chambers would be ready for\noccupancy by October 1, 1921. In reply\nto questions by Major F. H. La Guar?\ndia, President of the Board of Alder?\nmen, as to how much the building\nwould cost completed, the Comptroller\nsaid $8,.500,000 or a little more. He\ndeclared that the total amount would\nbe less than $10,000,000.\n\nFoodstuff Export Drops\n$360,000,000 in Year\nU. S. Import of Edibles In\ncreasts More Than\n$680,000,000\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 2.?Imports of\nfoodstuffs into the United States during\nthe fiscal year just ended increased by\nmore than $680,000,000 over 1919. while\nexports of foodstuffs in 1920 show a\ndecrease of more than $360,000,000,\n?according to foreign trade figures\nissued to-day by the Department of\nCommerce.\nFoodstuffs imported during 1920,\ntotalled $1,513,776,309, compared with\n$832,422,991 in 1919. Exports of the\nsame commodities in 1920 amounted to\n$2,141,193,130, as against $2,502,852,400\nduring 1919.\nCrude materials for u=c in manufact?\nuring imported in 1920 totalled $2,141,\n644.621, ?d with Ji.250.6T4.773\nH *r\n118,112 In 192?, against $1,226,393,137\nJti L\\}.J.\nroadway at 39- Street\nsir?ifi^raig^iai!i-,'-iar!!-; \"z, asistir v\nCompl?e^toWear Clothes\nREADY-TO SLIP RIGHT-ON\ntailored (Bv^4 jMerchanifailor\nTut Just ^tailed Retailer\nIf you take the stand that Ready*\nMade Clothes are \"all alike\", we\nwill make you take it back. In no\npart or process, from the selection\nof the woolens to the perfection\nof the fit, are our ?leady-For?\nWear Garments \"ready-made\" in\nthe common and commercial sense\nfr E are Merchant Tailors, 'whose Clothes\nare cut by Custom Technicians only, em?\nbodying all the ideals and individuality,\nall the patience and pride of Finest Cus?\ntom Handiwork, ready'to-slip-right-on\n^Priced *Ry HTie Qroducor\n\ns\nWill YOU Profit by the Experience of the\nRalston Purina Company?\nThe Ralston Purina Company of\n?3tLou?s,Mo.,isusing 75 Dictaphones\nin its various departments. Mr. R. A.\nBlack, Treasurer, says: \"The Rals?\nton Purina Company considers\nThe Dictaphone indispensable. In\nfact, it is our firm conviction that we\ncould not, nor would we undertake\nto get along without it; especially now\nthat we know what The Dictaphone\nis accomplishing for us today.**\nWhether your office is large of\nsmall, we are ready to install\nThe Dictaphone, to give you a work?\ning demonstration of how its use\nspeeds up letter production and saves\nthe time of both operator and execu?\ntive. Give The Dictaphone a trial\nin your office on a definite basis of\nspeed, accuracy, and economy.\nT?E\nRef. U. i. Pat. Off. ?f,J Foreign Cououie?\nThe Shortest Route to the Mail-Chute\"\nGoodrich Rubber Company, Kansas\nCity, Mo., ?ay: \"With us speed is the thing.\nTo secure it, we installed 23 Dictaphones and\ncentralized our typing department The re?\nsult, has been a decided increase in speed\nand a material increase in volume of cor?\nrespondence handled daily.\"\nHaywood Bros. Wakefield Co., New\nYork, N. Y. E. StaufTer, Mgr., says: \"The\n12 Dictaphones used in our various depart?\nments measure up to all our requirements\nfor speed, accuracy, and efficiency. Our\ndictation is never held up. This makes\nfor large savings in time and expense.\"\nThe Creamery Package Mf g. Company,\nChicago, 111. P. R. Durdy, Comptroller,\nsays: \"The 22 Dictaphones, used in all\nour departments, have proved to be\ntime-and-money savers in this office.\nThey certainly save the time of both opera?\ntor and dictator.\"\nAmerican National Bank, San\nFrancisco, California. 1. H. Sanborn,\nVice-President, says: \"Although we have\nbeen using The Dictaphone for a little\nmore than a year, the results have proved\nto us that The Dictaphone facilitates our\nwork and speeds up letter production with?\nout adding to our cost.\"\nPhone or write for convincing demonstration in your office, on your work\nTHE DICTAPHONE, Phone Worth 7250-Call at 280 Broadway, New York\nOffice also located in Newark, N. J.\nIt trat ?me Dictaphone, trade-marked \"The Dictaphone,*' made and merchandised by the Columbia Graphophone Co.\nragai?&a&$3iiL&;,t ,*x?Miw??%;a&i&?uasm","height":"25086","width":"19950"}}
